<subSubSection id="C3253E8DBF3FC237C961B36EE5061D80" lastPageId="52" lastPageNumber="205" pageId="48" pageNumber="201" type="description">
<paragraph id="8B806D06BF3FC233C961B36EE3A31922" blockId="48.[1081,1243,1371,1395]" box="[1081,1243,1371,1395]" pageId="48" pageNumber="201">
<figureCitation id="13047183BF3FC233C961B36EE3A31922" box="[1081,1243,1371,1395]" captionStart="Text-fig" captionStartId="53.[125,206,1655,1676]" captionTargetBox="[128,1440,151,1634]" captionTargetId="figure-149@53.[125,877,144,911]" captionTargetPageId="53" captionText="Text-fig. 33. Scanning electron microscope (SEM) images of tectate-punctate pollen from probable coprolite (not shown); Torres Vedras locality, Portugal. a–c) Monocolpate pollen grains in distal view (a, b) showing poorly defined aperture and punctate surface of the tectum (c) of the grain in (b); d) Pollen grain showing slightly rugulate surface of tectum; aperture not visible. Specimens, TV44-S137906-06 (a–c), TV44-S137906-08 (d). Scale bars 6 Μm (a, b, d), 3 Μm (c)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5386312" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5386312/files/figure.png" pageId="48" pageNumber="201">Text-fig. 33a–d</figureCitation>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B806D06BF3FC233CE29B3BFE4941AB2" blockId="48.[843,1482,1418,1763]" pageId="48" pageNumber="201">
<materialsCitation id="3B57675BBF3FC233CE29B3BFE4901AB2" collectionCode="S" pageId="48" pageNumber="201" specimenCode="S137906" specimenCount="1">
R e m a r k s. Several large tectate-punctate and apparently monocolpate pollen grains occur in a coprolite/ pollen clump (specimen 
<specimenCode id="DB99C57DBF3FC233C93EB3FFE3BE19B3" box="[1126,1222,1482,1506]" collectionCode="S" country="Sweden" lsid="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:15668" name="Department of Botany, Swedish Museum of Natural History" pageId="48" pageNumber="201" type="Herbarium">S137906</specimenCode>
) together with a wide range of other pollen 
<typeStatus id="5484D3A4BF3FC233C919B3DEE3051A52" box="[1089,1149,1515,1539]" pageId="48" pageNumber="201">types</typeStatus>
. The pollen grains are almost circular in polar view, about 26–30 µm in diameter, and with a short, apparently circular aperture (
<figureCitation id="13047183BF3FC233C987B01EE2F31A12" box="[1247,1419,1579,1603]" captionStart="Text-fig" captionStartId="53.[125,206,1655,1676]" captionTargetBox="[128,1440,151,1634]" captionTargetId="figure-149@53.[125,877,144,911]" captionTargetPageId="53" captionText="Text-fig. 33. Scanning electron microscope (SEM) images of tectate-punctate pollen from probable coprolite (not shown); Torres Vedras locality, Portugal. a–c) Monocolpate pollen grains in distal view (a, b) showing poorly defined aperture and punctate surface of the tectum (c) of the grain in (b); d) Pollen grain showing slightly rugulate surface of tectum; aperture not visible. Specimens, TV44-S137906-06 (a–c), TV44-S137906-08 (d). Scale bars 6 Μm (a, b, d), 3 Μm (c)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5386312" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5386312/files/figure.png" pageId="48" pageNumber="201">Text-fig. 33a, b</figureCitation>
). The exine surface is smooth with densely spaced perforations of various sizes (
<figureCitation id="13047183BF3FC233C95AB05EE3D21AD2" box="[1026,1194,1643,1667]" captionStart="Text-fig" captionStartId="53.[125,206,1655,1676]" captionTargetBox="[128,1440,151,1634]" captionTargetId="figure-149@53.[125,877,144,911]" captionTargetPageId="53" captionText="Text-fig. 33. Scanning electron microscope (SEM) images of tectate-punctate pollen from probable coprolite (not shown); Torres Vedras locality, Portugal. a–c) Monocolpate pollen grains in distal view (a, b) showing poorly defined aperture and punctate surface of the tectum (c) of the grain in (b); d) Pollen grain showing slightly rugulate surface of tectum; aperture not visible. Specimens, TV44-S137906-06 (a–c), TV44-S137906-08 (d). Scale bars 6 Μm (a, b, d), 3 Μm (c)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5386312" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5386312/files/figure.png" pageId="48" pageNumber="201">Text-fig. 33a–c</figureCitation>
). One specimen seen from the proximal side has a somewhat rugulate surface (Textfig. 33d), and it is unknown whether this grain belongs to a separate taxon
</materialsCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B806D06BF3FC232CE29B0CEE6191B90" blockId="48.[843,1482,1786,2100]" lastBlockId="49.[106,745,1833,2081]" lastPageId="49" lastPageNumber="202" pageId="48" pageNumber="201">
A f f i n i t y a n d o t h e r o c c u r r e n c e s. Pollen resembling these tectate grains have not been observed in other Early Cretaceous floras from 
<collectingCountry id="F3282D96BF3FC233C9A7B10EE2211B02" box="[1279,1369,1851,1875]" name="Portugal" pageId="48" pageNumber="201">Portugal</collectingCountry>
and their systematic affinity is uncertain. Although the grains show certain similarities with other tectate grains from the Torres Vedras locality that are thought to be of piperalean affinity (see above), they differ in several features, especially in the shorter and broader aperture, and they may not be related. These pollen grains are also much larger than the grains associated with 
<taxonomicName id="4C3F1685BF3FC233CEA3BE29E3E91462" box="[1019,1169,2076,2099]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Magnoliopsida (awaiting allocation)" genus="Appomattoxia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Magnoliopsida (awaiting allocation)" pageId="48" pageNumber="201" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B94BB114BF3FC233CEA3BE29E3E91462" box="[1019,1169,2076,2099]" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="201">Appomattoxia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C3F1685BF3FC233C992BE29E2341465" authorityName="Friis &amp; Crane &amp; Pedersen" authorityYear="2019" box="[1226,1356,2076,2100]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Chloranthaceae" genus="Appofructus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Chloranthales" pageId="48" pageNumber="201" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B94BB114BF3FC233C992BE29E2341465" box="[1226,1356,2076,2100]" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="201">Appofructus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, as well as putatively related grains assigned to 
<taxonomicName id="4C3F1685BF3EC232CCAAB11FE53E1B10" authorityName="E. M. FRIIS, P. R. CRANE et K. R. PEDERSEN" authorityYear="2019" box="[498,582,1834,1857]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Chloranthaceae" genus="Dejaxia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Chloranthales" pageId="49" pageNumber="202" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B94BB114BF3EC232CCAAB11FE53E1B10" box="[498,582,1834,1857]" italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="202">Dejaxia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C3F1685BF3EC232CF24B11FE59A1B10" authorityName="E. M. FRIIS, P. R. CRANE et K. R. PEDERSEN" authorityYear="2019" box="[636,738,1834,1857]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Chloranthaceae" genus="Goczania" kingdom="Plantae" order="Chloranthales" pageId="49" pageNumber="202" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B94BB114BF3EC232CF24B11FE59A1B10" box="[636,738,1834,1857]" italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="202">Goczania</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and also lack the fine spines on the tectum surface. The pollen grains in the coprolite also differ from the the pollen of 
<taxonomicName id="4C3F1685BF3EC232CDDFB1BFE79E1BF0" authorityName="E. M. FRIIS, P. R. CRANE et K. R. PEDERSEN" authorityYear="2019" box="[135,230,1930,1953]" class="Amphibia" family="Rhacophoridae" genus="Burgeria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anura" pageId="49" pageNumber="202" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B94BB114BF3EC232CDDFB1BFE79E1BF0" box="[135,230,1930,1953]" italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="202">Burgeria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, mainly in the configuration of the aperture and different exine surface.
</paragraph>
<caption id="DF403D8EBF3EC232CD25B010E4511ABB" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5386301" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5386301" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5386301/files/figure.png" pageId="49" pageNumber="202" startId="49.[125,206,1573,1594]" targetBox="[128,1440,151,1552]" targetPageId="49">
<paragraph id="8B806D06BF3EC232CD25B010E4511ABB" blockId="49.[125,1440,1573,1770]" pageId="49" pageNumber="202">
Text-fig. 30. Scanning electron microscope (SEM) images of monocolpate pollen of 
<taxonomicName id="4C3F1685BF3EC232CEEDB010E3FB1A6B" authority="Friis &amp; Crane &amp; Pedersen, 2019" authorityName="Friis &amp; Crane &amp; Pedersen" authorityYear="2019" box="[949,1155,1573,1594]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Chloranthaceae" genus="Dejaxia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Chloranthales" pageId="49" pageNumber="202" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="brevicolpites" status="gen. et sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="B94BB114BF3EC232CEEDB010E3FB1A6B" bold="true" box="[949,1155,1573,1594]" italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="202">Dejaxia brevicolpites</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A2780C6FBF3EC232C9DFB010E26E1A6B" box="[1159,1302,1573,1594]" pageId="49" pageNumber="202" rank="species">gen. et sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
from a pollen clump; Torres Vedras locality, Portugal. a) Holotype; pollen clump (possible single pollen sac) that yielded the pollen in this Textfigure; b, c) Group of almost spherical pollen grains showing the irregularly undulating psilate tectum and abundant orbicules; d–g) Pollen grains showing the short colpi with a granular aperture membrane (d, f) and the irregularly undulating psilate tectum with scattered small perforations; note abundant orbicules (g); h) Pollen grain in proximal view showing the irregularly undulating psilate tectum resulting from the depressions around the perforations in the pollen wall. Specimen, TV44-S137909 (holotype). Scale bars 300 Μm (a), 30 Μm (b), 12 Μm (c), 6 Μm (d–h).
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="8B806D06BF3EC237CDC8B1FFE5061D80" blockId="49.[106,745,1833,2081]" lastBlockId="52.[129,768,151,465]" lastPageId="52" lastPageNumber="205" pageId="49" pageNumber="202">
In their general morphology, size and apparently thick pollen wall these tectate pollen grains are more similar to grains of 
<emphasis id="B94BB114BF3EC232CDA5BE3CE6FC1470" box="[253,388,2057,2081]" italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="202">Tucanopollis</emphasis>
described from the Barremianearly Aptian of 
<collectingCountry id="F3282D96BF3EC232CEBAB11CE35A1B10" box="[994,1058,1833,1857]" name="Brazil" pageId="49" pageNumber="202">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFAE10F7BF3EC232C96BB11CE3C31B13" author="Regali, M. S. P." box="[1075,1211,1833,1858]" pageId="49" pageNumber="202" pagination="395 - 402" refId="ref81814" refString="Regali, M. S. P. (1989): Tucanopollis, um genero novo das angiospermas primitivas [Tucanopollis, a new genus of primitive angiosperms]. - Boletim de Geociencias da Petrobras, 3: 395 - 402. (in Portugese)" type="journal article" year="1989">Regali 1989</bibRefCitation>
), but lack the echinate supratectal ornamentation and the characteristic verrucate colpus membrane of 
<emphasis id="B94BB114BF3EC232C94CB15CE3E31BD0" box="[1044,1179,1897,1921]" italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="202">Tucanopollis</emphasis>
pollen. The Torres Vedras grains are also similar to dispersed pollen described from the Early Cretaceous of southern 
<collectingCountry id="F3282D96BF3EC232C93BB19CE3C21B90" box="[1123,1210,1961,1985]" name="United Kingdom" pageId="49" pageNumber="202">England</collectingCountry>
as CfA Barremian- 
<emphasis id="B94BB114BF3EC232C8D9B19FE2D41B90" box="[1409,1452,1962,1985]" italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="202">ring</emphasis>
, but the Torres Vedras grains are larger and lack the fine spines on the tectum surface (Hughes 1994). The pollen grains from the coprolite are also similar to grains assigned to the extinct genus 
<emphasis id="B94BB114BF3BC237CD9CB6A2E63A1CFE" box="[196,322,151,175]" italics="true" pageId="52" pageNumber="205">Crassipollis</emphasis>
GÓCZAN et JUHÁSZ in the very thick tectate pollen wall. However, all six species of 
<emphasis id="B94BB114BF3BC237CF40B68DE5EE1C81" box="[536,662,184,208]" italics="true" pageId="52" pageNumber="205">Crassipollis</emphasis>
described by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFAE10F7BF3BC237CDFCB6EDE6BA1CA1" author="Goczan, F. &amp; Juhasz, M." box="[164,450,216,240]" pageId="52" pageNumber="205" pagination="289 - 319" refId="ref77570" refString="Goczan, F., Juhasz, M. (1984): Monosulcate pollen grains of angiosperms from Hungarian Albian sediments I. - Acta Botanica Hungarica, 30: 289 - 319." type="journal article" year="1984">Góczan and Juhász (1984)</bibRefCitation>
from the Albian of 
<collectingCountry id="F3282D96BF3BC237CFC7B6EDE5841CA1" box="[671,764,216,240]" name="Hungary" pageId="52" pageNumber="205">Hungary</collectingCountry>
, including the 
<typeStatus id="5484D3A4BF3BC237CC54B6CCE6411D40" box="[268,313,249,273]" pageId="52" pageNumber="205">type</typeStatus>
species, are characterized by a long, straight colpus that is sometimes broader at each end. This contrasts with the more rounded aperture seen in specimens from the Torres Vedras coprolite. Pollen grains assigned to 
<emphasis id="B94BB114BF3BC237CFD9B76CE5871D20" box="[641,767,345,369]" italics="true" pageId="52" pageNumber="205">Crassipollis</emphasis>
from the Barremian of Spain (
<bibRefCitation id="EFAE10F7BF3BC237CCEBB74CE5801DC0" author="Villanueva-Amadoz, U. &amp; Sender, L. M. &amp; Royo-Torres, R. &amp; Verdu, F. J. &amp; Pons, D. &amp; Alcala, L. &amp; Diez, J. B." box="[435,760,377,401]" pageId="52" pageNumber="205" pagination="374 - 388" refId="ref84037" refString="Villanueva-Amadoz, U., Sender, L. M., Royo-Torres, R., Verdu, F. J., Pons, D., Alcala, L., Diez, J. B. (2015): Palaeobotanical remains associated with dinosaur fossils from the Camarillas Formation (Barremian) of Galve (Teruel, Spain). - Historical Biology, 27: 374 - 388. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 08912963.2014.931385" type="journal article" year="2015">Villanueva-Amadoz et al. 2015</bibRefCitation>
) are more similar to the Torres Vedras grains in their aperture configuration, but the Spanish grains are smaller.
</paragraph>
